In article <strnlghtC8FIn5.IJF@netcom.com> strnlght@netcom.com (David Sternlight) writes:
>In article <CDUPREE.93Jun10121056@bruins.oracle> cdupree@oracle (Chuck
>Dupree) writes:
>
>>Of course, this could only be determined by a panel of experts with
>>relevant security clearances, because anything NSA proposes is
>>presumably beyond public ideas of state-of-the-art.
>
>This summarizes the problem of civilian review of highly classified matters
>very nicely. At some point you have to trust someone, and it can't be every
>Tom, Dick or Mary or you lose the security you're trying to preserve.

If you require security clearances, or even simple nondisclosure
agreements, before you allow the _best_ civilian experts in cryptology
review more advanced technique...

... who's going to improve the civilian techniques?  Your best people,
who could have made the dicoveries independently, are now restricted
from revealing this information!  They can't even provide encouragement
to their civilian peers.

